  "prompt": "Are there any websites like DAAD for masters in US?",
  "response": "While DAAD (German Academic Exchange Service) is a specific organization focused on promoting academic exchange between Germany and other countries, primarily offering funding for German students studying abroad and international students studying in Germany, there isn't a single direct equivalent for *specifically* funding masters studies in the US.  Instead, you need to look at several different categories of resources:\n\n**1. Funding Databases and Search Engines:**\n\n*   **IIE Scholarship Search:** Managed by the Institute of International Education (IIE), this is a comprehensive database of scholarships, fellowships, and grants for international students.  You can filter by subject area, country of study (USA), and level of study (Masters).  [https://www.iie.org/](https://www.iie.org/)\n*   **EduPASS:** This website focuses on financial aid for international students studying in the US.  It has information on scholarships, loans, and other funding sources. [https://www.edupass.org/](https://www.edupass.org/)\n*   **Scholarship America:** While primarily focused on US students, sometimes they offer scholarships open to international students.  Worth checking. [https://scholarshipamerica.org/](https://scholarshipamerica.org/)\n*   **ProFellow:**  Focuses heavily on fellowships, including those for graduate study in the US.  A great resource, though less specific to US funding than IIE or EduPASS. [https://www.profellow.com/](https://www.profellow.com/)\n*   **InternationalStudent.com:** Offers a database of scholarships specifically for international students studying in the US.  [https://www.internationalstudent.com/](https://www.internationalstudent.com/)\n*   **Financial Aid websites run by specific universities:** Once you have a list of universities you're interested in, visit their Financial Aid or Graduate Admissions websites *directly*.  They will often list internal scholarships, fellowships, and assistantships specific to their programs, which are often less competitive than external, nationally advertised scholarships.\n\n**2. Government Funding Agencies (Your Home Country):**\n\n*   **Crucially, check with your own government's funding agencies or educational exchange programs.**  Many countries have organizations similar to DAAD that offer scholarships to their citizens for studying abroad. This is often the most fruitful avenue.  Search \"[Your Country] study abroad scholarship\" or \"[Your Country] education ministry scholarships.\"\n\n**3. Discipline-Specific Organizations:**\n\n*   **Professional Associations:**  Many professional associations and societies (e.g., IEEE for engineering, ACM for computer science, APS for physics, etc.) offer scholarships or grants to students pursuing advanced degrees in their respective fields.  These are often targeted, requiring specific research interests or project proposals.\n*   **Research Institutes:** Research institutes often have funding for graduate students engaged in relevant research areas.\n\n**4. US University Funding:**\n\n*   **Graduate Assistantships (Teaching or Research):** Most US universities offer graduate assistantships (TA or RA positions) that provide tuition waivers and a stipend in exchange for teaching or research work. This is often the *primary* way students fund their masters degrees in the US, particularly in STEM fields.  These are typically awarded by the academic department you're applying to.\n*   **University Fellowships:** Many universities also have competitive internal fellowships that provide funding for outstanding graduate students.  Again, these are applied for as part of your application to the graduate program.\n\n**Key Differences from DAAD and Things to Keep in Mind:**\n\n*   **Decentralization:** Unlike DAAD, which is a centralized German organization, funding for graduate study in the US is much more decentralized. You need to investigate a wide range of sources: your home country's agencies, US universities, and discipline-specific organizations.\n*   **Competition:** Funding for international students in the US is generally highly competitive.\n*   **Emphasis on Merit:** Funding is often heavily based on academic merit and research potential.  Strong grades, test scores (GRE, TOEFL/IELTS), and research experience are crucial.\n*   **Application Deadlines:** Scholarship and funding application deadlines are often *much earlier* than program application deadlines.  Plan ahead!\n*   **Field Matters:** Funding availability varies significantly depending on your field of study.  STEM fields generally have more funding opportunities than humanities or social sciences.\n*   **Citizenship Restrictions:**  Many scholarships have citizenship restrictions, so carefully review eligibility criteria.\n\n**In summary, to find funding for a masters degree in the US, you need to be proactive and research a variety of sources, focusing on:**\n\n1.  **Your home country's funding agencies.**\n2.  **US university financial aid websites.**\n3.  **General scholarship databases like IIE and EduPASS.**\n4.  **Discipline-specific organizations and research institutes.**\n5.  **Understanding and applying for graduate assistantships (TA/RA) at the universities you're interested in.**\n\nGood luck with your search!\n",
